Food to blame for European inflation
The main reason for the increase in inflation measured in the euro area is the rapidly rising food prices.
In the 13 euro area countries, the inflation rate in November was higher than expected - according to the 2.6 percent in October, an annual inflation rate of 3.1 percent was recorded, according to the EU Statistical Office in Luxembourg.
Official forecasts are only 3 percent, Bloomberg reported.
Contrary to the American, British, and Canadian central banks, the European Central Bank (ECB) has not lowered the leitzsins; in its discretion, the reduction in interest rates would favour the rise in commodity prices and the slight fall in unemployment, the emergence of an inflation spiral.
The ECB strives to keep inflation rates below two percent, or at least close to the two percent mark.
According to an analyst, the ECB is in the middle of the gap: inflation must be "agreed" to exclude future need for action.
With 3.3 per cent, the inflation rate reached a 12-year high in Germany in November; in Spain, the rate climbed from 3.6 to 4.1 per cent.
The increase in inflation in the euro area is responsible for the rise in food and energy prices.
The MATIF wheat quotations rose by 88 percent, and the price for soybeans also reached a record high since 1973.
Food oil and dairy products were also subject to considerable inflation in 2007.
The world market price for crude oil rose by 52 percent this year – last month, the price per barrel of black gold reached almost $100.
According to the ECB, inflation will rise from 2.1 to 2.5 percent in 2008, but is expected to fall to 1.9 percent in 2009.
For the next 3-4 months, analysts expect a 3-percent inflation rate, but the annual average rate is 2.1 per cent.
For 2008, experts expect the ECB to lower interest rates twice.
