In many places, disinfectants are saved
This year, more than a thousand infections have been recorded in hospitals due to improper use of antibiotics.
The hygienic conditions in hospitals, the overcrowding of beds, the overload of staff - all factors that are not exactly conducive to the containment of infections, according to the lead physician of the National Epidemiology Center.
In many places, disinfectants are also saved.
In the traumatology department of J<0xC3><0xA1>nos Hospital, an MRSA infection has recently been diagnosed.
The antibiotic-resistant bacterium was found in a male patient who was hospitalized after a serious accident.
The patient was isolated.
At the beginning of the year there was already a similar infection here.
The injured person in a serious car accident was discharged from the hospital, but a little later the man had to return with an MRSA infection. An important operation has not yet been performed because of the bacterium, which is still in the patient's body.
By December 10, 1094, infections caused by multi-resistant pathogens were reported to the National Nosocomialis Surveillance System, according to Karolina Böröcz, the lead physician of the National Epidemiology Center.
So many infections caused by multi-resistant pathogens have been registered in hospitals with certainty, but the dark digit is likely to be higher.
About two-thirds of infections (683 cases) were caused by MRSA, the Staphylococcus aureus resistant to methicillin oxacillin.
The Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacterium carries about a third of people in their nose without causing a disease.
SA-related infections (such as throat inflammation, tonsillitis, inflammation of the skin or wounds) usually respond well to antibiotics, they are well curable.
However, if the agents are used too highly or improperly, antibiotics-resistant are produced from the well-responding bacteria, which rapidly spread in hospitals under appropriate conditions.
Especially in patients with weakened, or permanently poorly functioning immune systems, but also in older, or patients with low body weight, these bacteria can cause serious infections, such as wound infection or blood poisoning, i.e. sepsis.
According to the medical director of J<0xC3><0xA1>nos Hospital, MRSA infection is nothing special, such incidents are part of everyday hospital life.
One must not confuse the infection with the epidemic, Tibor Nyulasi warned - MRSA only does not exist where it is not sought.
Resistant to antibiotics
"Such patients are isolated, the caregivers wear rubber gloves and masks in the care, and we have the antibiotics necessary for the treatment" - Tibor Nyulasi.
While patients are being examined for MRSA, an infection cannot always be avoided.
Samples taken too rarely
The majority of MRSA-induced infections in hospitals would be preventable, but the current prevailing conditions and circumstances are unfavorable for the prevention of the emergence or spread of the multi-resistant pathogen, says Karolina Böröcz.
After this infection occurs predominantly in hospitals and retirement homes, the hospitals should examine the patients who have been hospitalised and isolate MRSA-infected patients immediately.
In Hungarian hospitals, however, microbiological sampling is not practiced as often.
Not least because there are no subsidies for this investigation on the part of the state health insurance company.
Most cases therefore only come to light when the patient already has a noticeable MRSA infection, according to the medical director of the epidemiology center.
From the European Union there are strict recommendations on the appropriate use of antibiotics in human medicine, but there are also guidelines for the treatment of certain infections and diseases in Hungary.
Antibiotic therapies should be targeted, that is, microbiological investigations are necessary so that no resistance to the drug can form, but this directive is not always adhered to by hospitals.
Among the outpatients, or patients in primary care, microbiological samples were even rarer, says Karolina Böröcz.
Saved for disinfectants
Scientific evidence shows that MRSA is most often transmitted from one patient to another by the caregiver.
This is precisely why hand washing, or wearing gloves and masks, is of great importance, but there are also significant deficiencies in this area in hospitals.
MRSA is transmitted through droplet infection or contact, but in domestic hospitals there is not always the possibility to isolate the infected patient.
The rooms are even often overcrowded, the beds nestled close to each other, although there should be a distance of at least 1.5 meters between them from an epidemiological point of view.
As Karolina Böröcz notes further, unfortunately, in the less well-off hospitals, it even happens that disinfectants are saved, there are few caregivers, many patients - all factors that favor the emergence of infections.
Such infections are proven to be far less common there, or the further spread of the pathogen can be stopped, where these protective measures are observed, says Karolina Böröcz.
Government program against MRSA
Getting MRSA infections under control causes huge costs to health insurance companies, so they are fought everywhere.
In England, for example, the prevention of MRSA, or its containment, was recorded in the government program.
After first signs, the program is successful - as published data show, the trend of MRSA infections in England is declining.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention (ECDC) has declared the prevention of the development of multi-resistant pathogens (including MRSA) and the prevention of infections in hospitals one of its priorities.
