Bulgaria, the real estate paradise of the EU
The development of the Bulgarian real estate market is fabulous - the whole of Europe is paying attention to the previously rarely mentioned Balkan state.
What, where, and who buys in the EU’s still cheapest market, but which is rapidly becoming more expensive?
An analysis of the Bulgarian Re/Max Division.
Bulgaria is undoubtedly the most sought-after patch for property purchases in the Eastern European region, with cheap ski apartments and seaside houses.
Between the mountains, the regions of Bansko, Borovec, Pamprovo and Vitosa are among the most popular, by the sea Albena, the "gold coast", the "sun coast", and the historic towns of Sozopol and Nessebar the racers, but real estate around Kavarna and Balcik are also increasingly in demand.
According to estimates by Re/Max analysts in Bulgaria, the country’s interior also attracts sooner or later investors, such as Veliko Tarnovo, Gabrovo, Elena, and Triavna, and also the extremely favorable area of Russe records more buyers.
The capital city of Sofia also offers tempting offers - commercial and office spaces offer the highest returns.
Bulgaria is on its way to becoming one of the most attractive European golfer paradises, thus attracting tourists in the two other seasons in addition to the summer and winter season.
For this reason, prospective investors are already buying in a large style, for example around Bansko.
According to analysts, people who buy real estate in Bulgaria are also seeking a change in their way of life.
Most buyers are English, but there are also prospects from France, Belgium, Spain, and more and more from Romania.
Investors from Malta and Cyprus are also present, while there are mainly Russian buyers at the Black Sea and in the ski resorts.
There are three groups of foreign buyers, says Georgij Jankov, Regional Director of Re/Max Bulgaria.
Those who want to settle down buy either revitalized properties by 50-100,000 euros, or run-down houses by 5-15.000 euros, which they then renovate themselves.
Good connectivity and accessibility as well as communication opportunities are great written, but also the proximity to a big city, shops and doctors are crucial for the buyers.
The second category includes those who are looking for a holiday home (Bulgaria was listed among the top ten holiday destinations of the Germans in December).
The third group consists of business people who invest with the aim of a medium- to long-term increase in value.
Real estate in the capital, meanwhile, is becoming increasingly expensive, due to the ever-growing demand.
Within the EU, real estate prices are the lowest in Bulgaria, but in the past five years there has been a price increase of 21 percent annually.
The cost of real estate prices far exceeds the increase in salaries.
Fodor and the six Hungarian percent
As Minister of the Environment G<0xC3><0xA1>bor Fodor announced, the expert meetings will end on Tuesday, and the debate on the international climate regime after 2012 will continue by the ministers on Wednesday after the official opening.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries consult on the Bali Roadmap, which sets the emission reduction measures for the period after 2012, i.e. after the end of the Kyoto Protocol.
There is currently a fierce debate between developed and developing countries.
The US has already signalled that they do not want to negotiate on concrete figures, but would be willing to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 25-40 percent by 2020 compared to 1990.
The other big question of the conference is whether the industrialised countries are ready to support developing countries financially and technologically in addition to reducing emissions.
An agreement on the support of developing countries has also been reached.
The adjustment fund under the Kyoto Protocol is to be managed by a 16-member Council, which is expected to be read in the UN Global Environment Facility (GEF), as in the “Piac és Profit”.
Hungary's 6%
On behalf of Hungary, Minister of the Environment G<0xC3><0xA1>bor Fodor supports the EU’s efforts to maintain its pioneering role in global climate action and to achieve a new international agreement by 2009.
The Minister stated that the EU will reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 20% by 2020 (measured at 1990 levels), regardless of whether or not the "Agreement after 2012" will be achieved successfully. The Union would even be willing to commit to a 30% reduction if other major industrialised countries of the world, or developing countries, are also willing to meet their commitments according to forces and responsibly.
G<0xC3><0xA1>bor Fodor stressed that the objective of the states that joined the Kyoto Protocol in 1997 was a reduction of only 5.2 percent, whereas the EU and its 15 member states had already committed themselves to a reduction of 8%.
Hungary's target is to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 6% compared to 1985-87 - a target that the country will fully meet, as can be seen in the Ministry of the Environment's press release.
The effort is high in Bali - after all, the long-term international climate agreement must be completed within two years, otherwise it would certainly not come into force until after 2012. In this case, the reduction project set out in the Kyoto Protocol would not follow a new, international emission reduction system, the importance of which has also been highlighted by the IPCC, the international, with the Nobel Peace Prize-winning scientific climate change committee of the UN.
As a result, the emission reduction would be delayed, and the increase in the Earth’s average temperature by more than 2°C would be unavoidable, which scientists say would have extremely serious and irreparable consequences.
British Army advertises on YouTube
Units of the British Army have published footage of operations in Iraq and Afghanistan in order to increase popularity on the video portal.
First, the British Air Force (RAF) discovered YouTube for itself: Special forces stationed in Afghanistan have been loading videos about Taliban-led operations into the network since March 2006, the BBC reports.
Shots shot with helmet-mounted miniature cameras are controlled at the Air Force base in Kandahar and then sent to London, where they are placed on the Internet.
Political message inevitable
Soldiers of the Air Force have already contributed 139 such recordings, their "channel" has been viewed more than 75,000 times.
The British Ministry of Defence was registered under "defenseheadquarters" in spring 2007 to publish videos about Iraqi and Afghan operations, but also the British Foreign Ministry (Commonwealth Office) and the Iraq-based international peacekeeping forces (MNFI) have their own YouTube channels.
Operation in Afghanistan
Originally, the Luftwaffe published the videos with the aim of recruiting soldiers, and, as the Ministry of Defence says, the contributions also serve the purpose of informing the population about the actual goals of foreign missions.
Propaganda of this kind is almost free compared to conventional television advertisements, defence expert Gordon Mackenzie told the BBC, but these videos always carry a certain level of political message in them, as they confirm the existence of the military measures decided by the government in their own way.
U.S. Advertise With Game
However, the army must also fight amateur shots, which, in addition to the carefully edited, censored shots, also make it on the net - such as those that show the death of the soldiers: in the somewhat hypocritical, "official" propaganda films, the losses are spoken at most, but the bloody sides of the war are not shown.
Of the war scenes in Iraq and Afghanistan, by the way, numerous videos filmed in use have already been uploaded to the platform, but this "genus" has only recently been discovered by the British for themselves.
The Americans, however, advertise in a slightly different way, namely with the free downloadable shooting game "America's Army", in which the player can slip into the soldier's skin as part of a more or less lifelike simulation.
