Holidays aren’t everywhere holidays
In Hungary, holidays are strictly regulated by law, so that the practice of re-disposing the working days around the holidays has now become established, but the coming year will give us less such days.
Also in the EU and in America, something else is understood as "celebrity day".
The Hungarian legal system distinguishes between public holidays and work-free days.
Work-free days are usually ecclesiastical holidays, or are related to significant historical events.
For example, we also celebrate New Year: both the last day of the old and the first day of the new year are work-free days – the latter alone so that the New Year’s celebrations can rest.
Throughout the year we have a total of fourteen holidays.
The state holidays are March 15th, which commemorates the Revolution of 1848, and October 23rd, the Memorial Day of the Revolution of 1956.
On the 20th of August, the founding of the state, on the 1st of May, the work is celebrated, on the 1st and 2nd of November, we commemorate our dead.
In addition, there are two holidays to Easter, Pentecost, and Christmas each.
Since our state, national, or religious holidays rarely fall on a weekend, the practice of “working day shift” has proven itself in cases where we would only work one day before or after the holiday.
The price of extended weekends, however, is that we have to work very well on Saturdays before, or go to school.
When this day, which falls before or after the holiday, is ultimately to be worked out, the Minister of Labour has for many years set out in his own decree.
The legislation applies to all employers and employees, to public servants and civil servants alike.
Exceptions are only companies and facilities in which the operation is continued without interruption, i.e. also on public holidays.
This year, the working order is only somewhat confused by the holidays at the end of the year: from December 24th, life in this country remains formal, since most of the days between Christmas and New Year's Eve take time off, or take the specially cancelled holiday.
In the next year, more holidays fall into the middle of the week, or to the end of the week, so that there will be fewer re-disposals on the working days than this year.
The calendar is first "turned upside down" around the day of work so that people can stay at home for four days at a time.
Saturday, April 26th will be a working day so that Friday, May 2nd can be a rest day.
The second re-disposal is related to the holiday on 23 October: On Saturday, 18 October you will have to finish the Friday, 24 October in advance.
The end of the year, however, will be completely marked by the holidays, after from December 24 everything will lie and remain, even if New Year’s Eve falls on a Wednesday.
Six Terrifying Little Things to Worry About Your Workmates
Emails that we forget to send, voice messages that we never receive - harmless lies that no longer stand out: they bring "color" to everyday life in the workplace.
The only question is whether you get used to these little inconveniences, or you better face the challenge and consciously try to avoid these misunderstandings for other annoying situations.
Tips.
"Sorry, I forgot to tell you that someone called from the marketing department," a colleague says.
Did you miss a meeting?
At best, you regret it and try to make amends by perhaps calling the marketing department and humbly confessing that you had forgotten to align the message (this is the less common method).
Most of the time, the case is dismissed with an apology.
Before engaging in embarrassing excuses, one should consider how to truly create unpleasant moments for one’s colleagues and try to avoid these situations consciously.
Borrowing something that doesn’t belong to you?
There’s hardly anything more nerve-wracking than grabbing a document, office supplies, or the phone, but it’s not there.
Yesterday the stapler was still on the desk - this morning it's gone?
Or is the lost ballpoint pen discovered on a colleague’s desk?
Without questions, you should not borrow anything from your colleagues, because they are rightly annoyed when they find that something has gone away.
So, don't put envelopes or post-it out of the office in your pocket, because it could hit you yourself: no more if you need it urgently.
Talk about the private life of colleagues?
There is no effective means of stopping a bargain that has already been made in the world.
Who did what with whom?
Where and why?
One should not tie the information (or conjectures) about the private life of colleagues to the nose if possible!
And if someone opens up and tells us his inner secret, we should not abuse that trust!
It is best to remain silent like a grave, rather than directing those who are not present, even if others are aware of the problems of the colleague.
Reported sick for no reason?
If you call in the office to report sick, citing painful headaches, because you just feel uncomfortable, or just want to rest, you should be aware of one thing: your own work, inadvertent completions, projects with fixed deadlines now have to be done by your colleagues instead of by yourself.
So don't play bad with your colleagues!
If you know the day before that you will not be able to get into the office the next day, or that something could come in between, which is why you have to stay at home, you should report it in time so that neither the colleagues nor the boss are unexpectedly confronted with the absence.
Summaries, checkers, phone calls
One is just deepened in his work, but is suddenly disturbed by the loud whims of the colleagues?
Do you want to hear a phone call that you shouldn’t have heard?
You should not bother your colleagues with buzzing, singing, loud conversations (which you carry across their heads), trampling, constantly shrieking or grumbling.
All of this can be very disturbing, even if they are not exactly immersed in a task (writing, planning, organizing).
Are the others always to blame?
If a project is not finished on time, one has forgotten to send an important letter or important messages, one should not seek the guilt of one’s own oblivion with others!
If possible, do not talk about the chaos in the office or the loud colleagues!
It is best to admit your mistakes and apologize if others were affected.
The question of how to make up for the mistake again, or how to make up for the failure, is all too appropriate!
In the office - a feeling like at home?
Training pants and sleeping: comfortable for home, but hasn’t lost anything in the office!
Not even then should you dress so casually if it would actually allow the workplace!
Just don't get too sloppy - you should respect both your colleagues and yourself to the extent that you dress appropriately in the office - if desired, also pretty and elegant!
