Cuba - the most beautiful island in the Caribbean
For visitors, it is truly an island of freedom.
Whatever you expect from your holiday, it will come true if you just choose the right one.
Golden and white beaches, high waves or a sea that is quiet like a pond.
Palms and All Inclusive with waiters offering pizza, ice cream and beguiling cocktails on the beach.
Kitesurfing, golf and roulette.
On the islands of the Caribbean you will find this to a large extent.
Only on one island you will find much more, and this island is Cuba, the largest and most beautiful of the Great Antilles.
At the time of the Spanish, Cuba was their bastion for the conquest of America.
Columbus called it the most beautiful place a human eye has ever seen.
Havana once became a camp or transit camp of treasures that the Spaniards had robbed in America and then transported to Europe.
Then came the American era.
The Hotel Nacional was built at the end of the 20th century.
It was built by one of the chiefs of the American mafia, Lucky Luciano, because everything that was considered a crime in the United States (especially during the Prohibition) was liked and supported in Cuba – drugs, gambling, prostitution.
Among his guests were among others.
Winston Churchill, Ava Gardner, Frank Sinatra.
High-rise buildings grew in Havana, across the wide boulevards, driving cars that were among the iconic symbols of the fifties of the last century.
Ernest Hemingway bought a property in San Francisco de Paula, near Havana, and in Coj<0xC3><0xAD>mar he had his yacht.
On the walls of the Bodeguita del Medio, stars of the show business and politicians from all over America left their signatures.
And today?
On the walls of the Bodeguita of Havana you can also leave your autograph.
At the bar at the Hotel Nacional you can mix cocktails as desired.
And the cult cars of the fifties continue to travel around in Havana to this day, because the once imported shigulis and fiats have long since fallen apart in the salty and humid air.
May Havana, especially its oldest part, have come down heavily, nowhere in the vicinity can you find as many wonderful colonial sights as right here.
Other places are being cleaned out, such as Trinidad.
In view of the fact that tourism brings much-needed money, there was a green light for this development.
In the last fifteen years, new hotels have emerged not only in Havana, but also in Varadero, on the coast of the province of Holgu<0xC3><0xAD>n and also on islands such as Cayo Coco, Cayo Guillermo and others.
Cuba still offers a marotte that is unique in the world and especially attracts railway lovers.
The sugar cane from remote plantations brought steam- and diesel-powered narrow-gauge tracks to the sugar factories.
Their fleet has not been renewed for decades, and this is where you can see clean and fully functioning locomotives, whose peers have long been in the museum elsewhere.
Excursion destinations
The most important places do not make up the majority of visitors to Cuba.
You don’t have to write about Varadero or Havana in detail anymore.
It remains to be mentioned that Hemingway’s already mentioned estate houses a museum whose visit to the one who likes this writer should not be missed.
The Vi<0xC3><0xB1>ales Valley in the west of the island is one of the most picturesque corners of Cuba.
The lush vegetation grows on limestone floor.
The mogotas, limestone hills and rocks, rise steeply from the valley floor, and in their hollow spaces, fertile soil accumulates, through which also weathered rock areas are covered by dense vegetation.
This valley is where perhaps the best Cuban tobacco is grown.
In its final form, you can meet him when you visit one of Havana’s cigar factories.
It may also seem interesting that the Chilean episode of the television series "Major Zeman" was filmed there.
Trinidad
An ancient city that was founded shortly after the Spanish colonized the island.
Fame and wealth brought her the trade of slaves and sugar.
The wealth was embodied in the beautiful beauty of the small town.
The Spanish colonial architecture, strongly influenced by the later French settlers, has hardly changed for four hundred years.
Trinidad, located between the sea and the Escambray Mountains, is such a remote place that there was no road there in the 1950s of the last century that would have connected the area to the rest of the country.
This isolation contributed to the fact that it remained unnoticed.
Nothing was built there, but therefore nothing was torn down, everyone was glad that he had a roof over his head.
If you have more than an afternoon for Trinidad, it is worth seeing interesting places in the area, such as the beach Playa Anc<0xC3><0xB3>n or the "Valley of Sugar Factories".
In the evening you should then go to the Casa de la M<0xC3><0xBA>sica, which revives after the darkness, and where the music does not remain until the morning.
Baracoa
This small town in the east of Cuba is known by some as the most beautiful of the island.
Surely this view is also influenced by the way there.
Both roads leading from Guant<0xC3><0xA1>namo have to overcome high and rugged mountains and run through a landscape that is barely touched by human intervention.
Thanks to its unspoilt nature, UNESCO has added this eastern outpost of Cuba to its World Heritage List.
There the best chocolate is made, in the church you show the cross of Columbus (in reality it was created about a hundred years after the trips of Columbus), and from the hill where the former castle, the current Hotel El Castillo, stands, you can see several table mountains, of which El Yunque is the most famous.
About the coffee, the rum, the cigars, the Sierra Maestra mountains, the Bay of Pigs and the island of Isla de Pinos, about the Tropicana Cabaret, the sanctuary of Cuban patron Caridad del Cobre, about the Santeria, an African religion to which the descendants of slaves profess, one could write many pages about all this.
As they say, look better with your own eyes.
Allies in Afghanistan are passive, Americans claim.
Too few soldiers and the lack of necessary equipment affect the course of the mission in Afghanistan, according to the United States.
According to Defense Secretary Robert Gates, NATO should draw up a concrete plan for the next few years.
The mission in Afghanistan did not go according to their ideas, the representatives of the countries in Scotland agreed on this, which have stationed units in the south of the country.
In addition to the growing resistance of the Taliban, the eight participating states also discuss further coordination plans among the allies.
While the United States, through its Secretary of Defense Robert Gates, called for more activity on NATO units, Britain sees priority in strengthening the authority of the Afghan government and in intensifying development aid.
“A forward development is noticeable in Afghanistan, but military power can only be part of the solution.
Another part is to enable residents to begin their own economic and security development,” said British Defence Minister Des Browne.
Ninety percent
The activity of the Afghan insurgents has reached the highest level in five years, according to the American army.
The number of acts of violence has increased by 27 per cent compared to the previous year, and in the southern province of Helmand even by sixty per cent.
NATO countries have deployed about 40,000 troops in Afghanistan, about a quarter of them in the southern territory.
According to the United States, however, the allies have reached an absolute limit in terms of the organization and equipment of the units.
Specifically, they are calling for more helicopters, soldiers and experts to train the Afghan units.
“We will have to seriously think about the concrete goals for the next time and about the way we can achieve them,” Gates said.
The Secretary-General of NATO, Jaap de Hoop, said the same thing today.
"I'm not happy with what we have at our disposal in Afghanistan on land and in the air.
We have about ninety percent of the soldiers and equipment we need, and that's too little," De Hoop told Reuters to conclude three-day talks with the Japanese government in Tokyo.
Who is Passive
In recent months, there has also been a dispute among the participating countries over whether all allies in Afghanistan are doing their best.
For example, Germany was criticized for its passivity.
"The Germans are relatively numerous in Afghanistan.
But they are stationed in areas where there is only a minimum of violence and the fighting demands for them are not as high as for us in the southern and eastern part of the country," Gates said.
The British tabloid Sun this week described the German soldiers as lazy furs.
"Afghan no-doors debunked: the Germans are making games while our boys are fighting," wrote the Sun in a post supplemented by photos of German soldiers playing table tennis.
The German Bildzeitung went over to counterattack and printed a picture of a British unit in a rugby competition in southern Afghanistan.
