For giving a name to a teddy bear, she was presented today to a court in Khartoum.
According to her lawyer, the British teacher, who had been charged with insulting Islam in Sudan, was sentenced by a court in Khartoum on Thursday evening to 15 days in prison and subsequent expulsion.
The British were accused of allowing six to seven-year-old students to name a teddy bear Mahomet, although any depiction of the Islamic Prophet is prohibited.
She deserved to be whipped.
After parents of students complained to the Sudanese Ministry of Culture several times, the 54-year-old elementary school teacher, who worked at Khartoum’s Unity High School, was taken to his home on Sunday and accused of insulting Islam under Article 125 of the Sudanese Criminal Code.
In fact, this matter begins in September, when the teacher asks her six- to seven-year-old students to choose a name for the class teddy.
The children suggest eight names, including Hassan, Abdullah and Mohammed, reports head of school Robert Boules.
Finally, when the class votes, 20 of 23 children choose Mohammed as their favorite given name.
Certainly, Mohammed is the name of the Islamic prophet, but above all a very common name in Sudan.
Afterwards, the children created a book for the class, with the photo of the bear on it and the caption My name is Mohammed.
The bear itself did not bear a sign with that name, but the problem is quite simple that the depiction of the Islamic prophet is considered an insult to Islam.
One of the Muslim colleagues of Gillian Gibbons, who teaches at the same school in Sudan, said he knows her well, and she would never have done anything that would have made her too close to a religious faith, I just regret that she asked the children to vote for a name, in his opinion this is just an innocent mistake.
An opinion that many students of the teacher share, describing it as very attentive to their students and as a person who never talks about religion in class.
Remember that the first name Mohammed is also the second most common given in the UK, for which there are 14 different spellings in English.
This name, often chosen by Muslim families, is considered a kind of homage to the Prophet (he is often given to the firstborn of a family).
But what are the rules regarding the use of this first name?
Can you give him a toy, for example?
This, of course, is a question of interpretation.
On Wednesday, there was no agreement at the last meeting in Vienna on the future status of the province.
At the end of the failure
The Serbs and Albanians from Kosovo ended a sixth and final discussion session in Baden, Austria, on Wednesday morning, without being able to overcome their controversy over the future status of the separatist province.
It is regrettable that the parties could not reach an agreement on the status, said European mediator Wolfgang Ischinger at a press conference in Vienna.
Emphasising that peace in the region is at stake, its American counterpart Frank Wilsner called on Belgrade and Pristina to fulfil their commitments to maintain peace and continue the talks beyond the end of the negotiations.
No acts of violence are expected in the immediate future, but we are at the beginning of a very difficult time, he added, suggesting that there are quite clear tensions.
End of mediations on 10 December
The Troika mediators, which unites the European Union, the United States and Russia, will meet in Serbia and Kosovo on Monday for the last time.
The future of the 90% of Albanian-speaking province could become clearer if Ischinger, Wilsner and Russian mediator Alexander Botsane-Khartchenko submit their report to the UN Security Council by December 10.
The talks of Baden, near Vienna, formed the sixth and final negotiating session since the Troika had been commissioned by the UN last August to conduct a new mediation.
Americans and Europeans expect their mediation mission to end on December 10.
The Russians, who had already blocked Kosovo’s approval of independence from the Security Council, insisted on continuing the negotiations beyond this deadline.
Russia was and remains the advocate of a negotiated solution, a consensual solution, Botsane-Khartchenko said.
A unilateral declaration of independence?
After Kosovo has been under the administration of the UN for eight years, the Western countries consider independence under the supervision of the EU to be the only solution with a future.
Pristina is ready to announce it unilaterally if the Security Council should not decide in their favour.
Belgrade insists on greater autonomy
Unfortunately, no agreement could be reached, the president of Kosovo’s autonomous authority, Fatmir Sejdiu, announced at the hotel in Baden, where since Monday these negotiations were held the last chance.
Hashim Thaci, former leader of the Kosovo rebellion and future prime minister of the province, shared his regrets.
However, he added that the Belgrade-proposed plan is part of the autonomy of a past that has led to murders and deportations.
Domino effect
Serbian President Boris Tradic, for his part, felt that a compromise should always be sought and warned the Albanian majority from Kosovo against the consequences of a unilateral declaration of independence of the province.
Belgrade believes that it is particularly responsible for a "domino effect" in a region that is so weakened by the independence wars of the 1990s.
For Serbia, this does not mean that a compromise would be impossible, he said.
On Tuesday, the Serbian delegation insisted that any decision should be taken solely in the Security Council, where its Russian ally holds a veto right.
Kosovo's parliament will have the last word
Only one decision from the ranks of the Security Council is acceptable to Serbia, Serbian Prime Minister Vojislav Kostunica said.
These negotiations took two years.
They must end as they began: in the Security Council.
