After being treated confidentially for more than 60 years, the Nazi archives of Bad Arolsen, which document the fates of 17.5 million victims of the Hitler regime, are now freely accessible.
The 47 million documents of the archive, which are housed at a total length of 27 km in Bad Arolsen, could not be seen until now, unless with a humanitarian intent, i.e. individual and name-related, i.e. at the request of a former victim or his relatives.
The eleven states, including Germany, France, Israel and the United States, agreed in May 2006 to make them accessible to researchers and historians.
After the ratification process of this Decision has been completed, the opening has been valid since yesterday.
Heikle Information
Historians' access to Bad Arolsen will allow them to conduct research, especially on the deportations of prisoners, the inmates of concentration camps and the health of forced laborers, explains Reto Meistern, head of these archives, which are administered by the International Committee of the Red Cross (CICR).
Until recently, several states, including Germany, were opposed to making these name-related documents available to the public, due to the delicate nature of certain information.
Like, for example, the alleged homosexuality or the mental disability of some deportation victims.
The inmates of the concentration camps or the detention orders issued by the Gestapo had been assembled after the war for a practical reason: to find civilians who had been deported or subjected to forced labour, and possibly to provide them with evidence of their arrest in order to pave the way for their compensation.
Today, more than 300 permanent employees still work on tens of thousands of personal inquiries in Bad Arolsen.
Nevertheless, part of the scientific community shows only a limited interest in access to Bad Arolsen.
Nothing fundamentally new can be expected in these documents, said Prof. Wolfgang Benz, Head of the Research Center for Antisemitism at the Technical University of Berlin, in 2006.
