New fears about natural gas dispute between Russia and Ukraine
A new price dispute is brewing between Ukraine and Russia, which increases the risk that Russian exports of fuel to Western Europe will be affected.
The majority of Russian natural gas exports to the European Union (EU) are directed by Ukraine and any dispute between the two nations is closely observed.
Kiev has warned that if Moscow increases the price it has to pay for natural gas, it will charge Russia higher transit fees.
An earlier conflict between the two states last year reduced deliveries to the EU states.
The recent dispute between Kiev and Moscow happens at a time when the Ukrainian government and the Russian state-run gas monopoly Gazprom are trying to reach an agreement on how much Ukraine has to pay for Russian natural gas in 2008.
According to Gazprom, Ukraine needs to be calculated more, as the Group has agreed to pay up to 50% additional for natural gas from neighbouring Turkmenistan.
Analysts say this could mean that Ukraine will have to pay 40% more for Gazprom imports.
“It’s important for us to use our arguments as one of the most important gas transit states in talks,” Ukraine’s economic minister Anatoli Kinakh told Reuters.
"The changing natural gas prices should undoubtedly be linked to our arguments regarding the amount of transit fees [to Western Europe] over Ukraine."
In the last major gas dispute between Moscow and Kiev in January 2006, Gazprom cut deliveries to Ukraine.
As a result, this led to a fall in exports to Western Europe, which dramatically increased prices.
Russian gas accounts for a quarter of the European Union’s supply.
Russia has the world’s largest gas deposits, but much of them remain underdeveloped.
As a result, Gazprom complements its own supplies with gas from Turkmenistan and other Central Asian former Soviet nations.
