Venus, despite its hostile atmosphere, is more similar to Earth than before: the European space probe "Venus Express" has discovered flashes in the atmosphere and wind vortices on the poles, as they occur on Earth in winter.
For almost three decades, scientists have suspected that it is flashing on Venus.
Now the European probe "Venus Express" has provided evidence - it detected electromagnetic waves on the edge of the atmosphere: the flashes on Venus shoot at an altitude of around 56 kilometers from cloud to cloud, reports Christopher Russel of the University of California in Los Angeles in the science magazine "Nature".
According to the famous "Ursuppen theory", lightning has created life on Earth: thunderstorms are said to have stimulated reactions in the ocean that led to the formation of amino acids, the building blocks of life.
Not so on Venus: “If there ever was life there, it must have been in very early history,” explains Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institution in Washington.
Today, there is hardly anything living on the surface of Venus: the atmosphere is about a hundred times denser than on Earth, sometimes temperatures of 500 degrees.
“Venus is perhaps the devil’s twin on Earth, but it’s a twin,” Russel said.
Why Venus, which is so similar to Earth in mass and size, has made such a completely different development, is the fundamental question of the Esa mission.
The launch of "Venus Express" in November 2005 was a milestone for Venus research, as since the early 1990s, no probe was specifically on the way to explore this planet.
The latest research results, which are now presented in several "Nature" articles, do not only underline the uniqueness of Venus within the solar system, according to the researchers.
"They also show that the similarities of our neighbor planet with the Earth are greater than initially assumed," Esa said.
In addition to the already known whirlwind at the North Pole, the researchers also found a cloud strudel at the South Pole, which rotates much faster.
The phenomenon is reminiscent of air currents in the terrestrial winter hemisphere, writes a team of researchers around Giuseppe Piccioni of the Italian Istituto di Astrofisica Spaziale e Fisica Cosmica.
The second-tenth planet of the solar system has almost the same mass as the Earth and is almost the same size with a diameter of 12,100 kilometers.
The planet, also known as the morning or evening star, orbits the sun in just 225 days.
But it is much slower: a Venus Day lasts 243 Earth days.
Although Venus barely recalls Earth at surface temperatures of 460 degrees Celsius and a pressure of 92 bar, scientists assume that both planets were formed under very similar conditions.
Both gathered water, which remained on Earth in oceans, but on which Venus was lost to space.
And while carbon dioxide is fixed on Earth in carbonate rocks, it makes up the majority of the atmosphere on Venus.
