These are not Warhol's boxes.
Anyone who combines the terms Sweden and wooden box thinks of Ikea, but not Andy Warhol.
Or is it?
Currently, in Sweden, fabricated wooden boxes cast dark shadows on Warhol's work directory.
Most of the forty-four Brillo boxes of the "type Stockholm" listed there are forgeries.
After the Swedish newspaper "Expressen" a few months ago raised doubts about the authenticity of Andy Warhol's Brillo boxes in 1968, internal research at the Moderna Museet in Stockholm now comes to a sobering conclusion: The six "Brillo boxes", which the former museum director Pontus Hultén has sold to the Moderna Museet in 1995 as a gift.
The prehistory is nested, a confusing chain of artistic and curatorial productions.
In 1964 Warhol created his first "Brillo Boxes" in New York, painted wooden boxes based on the red-blue-white design of the paperboard cartons of the "Brillo" soap powder.
An exhibition of his works at the Moderna Museet in 1968 exhibited - with Warhol's consent - hundreds of Brillo boxes made of cardboard: these were not from Warhol (for cost reasons) but were delivered directly from the Brillo Cartonagenfabrik.
These were not works of art, but their role models, mere exhibits.
At the same time, Warhol probably gave permission in 1968 to produce a few Brillo wooden boxes in Sweden, but they were not exhibited in the Moderna Museet.
Contemporary witnesses now speak of around fifteen boxes, which at the time were rightly incorporated into the history of art and auctions as authorized original Andy Warhol Brillo boxes with the name "Type Stockholm".
Some of them have made more than $100,000 in auctions.
The problem now is that the legendary museum director Pontus Hultén later falsely claimed that around a hundred wooden boxes were produced and exhibited in Sweden in 1968, which Warhol then left to him.
In fact, Hultén’s 105 boxes were only produced in 1990 in Malmö for an exhibition in St. Petersburg.
By that time, Warhol had been dead for three years.
Lars Byström, chief conservator at the Moderna Museet, in addition to the six museum-owned Brillo-Boxes, has also investigated three privately owned Swedish companies, two of which were made in Stockholm in 1968: their press-span plates were first grounded and smeared, and then white oil paint was applied with a brush.
The structure of the copies from 1990, on the other hand, reveals that the paint with a painting roller without primer was applied directly to the press clamping plate - moreover, it is not oil, but acrylic paint.
"These boxes were not authorized by the artist and should be removed from the official list of Andy Warhol's Brillo boxes," says the director of the Moderna Museet, Lars Nittve, "If the 'Andy Warhol Art Authentication Board' in New York does not come to a different conclusion, the Moderna Museet will classify the six boxes in its collection as copies/exhibition materials."
As early as July, the Authentication Board has announced that it will investigate the “heavy allegations” made in the matter of soap powder boxes.
But since then, you have been hiding in unrelenting silence.
